  "prompt": "Can a minor sue or be sued?",
  "response": "The ability of a minor to sue or be sued depends on the jurisdiction and specific circumstances:\n\n1. Generally:\n- Minors cannot directly file lawsuits on their own\n- A parent or legal guardian must act as a \"next friend\" or guardian ad litem to represent the minor's legal interests\n\n2. Suing:\n- A minor can sue through a representative\n- The representative can file a lawsuit on the minor's behalf\n- Some jurisdictions may require court approval\n\n3. Being sued:\n- Minors can technically be sued\n- Parents might be held liable for certain actions of their children\n- Legal proceedings may involve a guardian ad litem representing the minor's interests\n\n4. Statute of limitations:\n- Many jurisdictions \"toll\" (pause) the statute of limitations for minors\n- The legal time limit may be extended until the minor reaches adulthood\n\n5. Specific contexts:\n- Personal injury claims\n- Contract disputes\n- Property issues\n- Tort claims\n\n6. Limitations:\n- Minors generally cannot enter legally binding contracts\n- Court may appoint a special representative to protect the minor's rights\n\nNote: Specific rules vary by state and country, so local legal advice is recommended for precise details.",
